….. a higher effective tax of 32.6% in first quarter 2022 compared to 28.4% in first quarter 2021 led to slower growth in profit after tax to NGN96.82 billion by 31.3% year on year  MTN Nigeria Communications Plc (MTNN) in a statement released through the floor of the Nigerian Exchange showed 2022 first quarter unaudited results stood at 31.3% year on year increase in PAT to NGN96.82 billion while EPS stood at NGN4.76 representing 28.5% grew year on year. According to the report, the growth in earnings was driven mainly by the robust expansion in the top line grew by 22.2% year on year and expansion in EBITDA margin up by 151 bps to 54.6%, both of which completely offset the growth in OPEX  up by 20.5% year on year.  Other indicators are Service revenue grew by 22.2% year on year to NGN264.00 billion in first quarter 2022, due to the broad-based expansion across voice  increased by 6.5% year on year to 56.1% of revenue, data up by 54.5%year year representing 34.7% of revenue, and value-added services up by 46.5% year on year representing| 4.4% of revenue, also. The report disclosed that management have revealed that the growth in voice revenue was supported by increased gross connections and higher usage from its active customer base. We believe that voice revenue also benefitted from MTNN’s customer acquisition touchpoints and rural telephony initiatives, it was added. READ ALSO THIS: NCC, Stakeholders deliberates on Blockchain’s Benefits to Economy “We highlight that MTNN added 1.70 million subscribers in first quarter 2022, a continued improvement from the 1.00 million subscribers added in fourth quarter 2021. Also, management revealed that this was made possible by ramping up SIM registration and NIN enrollment capacity adding that approximately 60 million subscribers have submitted their NINs (as of 25 April 2022), representing about 85% of MTNN’s subscriber base (70.20 million as of first quarter 2022). The report further revealed that on data revenue grew by 54.5% year on year to NGN163.31 billion in first quarter 2022 while management noted an increase in its subscriber base and expanded 4G coverage and improved network capacity to support increasing data traffic drove the growth. Notably, the report stated the average MB per user rose by 69.8% year on year, enabling overall data traffic growth of 84.8% year on year. In addition, MTNN added about one million new smartphones to its network in first quarter 2022, while 4G penetration rose to 71.7% from 70.3% in 2021Full Year. EBITDA rose by 25.7% year on year to NGN257.15 billion in first quarter 20 22, supported by the faster growth in revenue representing 22.2% increase compared to network operating costs grow of 16.2% year on year. However, operating expenses grew significantly by 20.5% year on year on the back of increases in the Interconnect and roaming costs up by 14.8% year on year, Discounts and commissions up by 5.2% year on year, and Advertisements, sponsorships and sales promotions grew by 64.9% year on year lines. Notwithstanding the elevated cost pressures, EBITDA margin expanded by 151bps to 54.6% in first quarter 2022 compare with first quarter 2021 which stood at 53.1%.  Other indicators are: Net finance cost rose by 18.7% year on year in first quarter 2022 due to the growth in finance cost by 28.6% year on year amid a substantial increase in finance income by 273.8% year on year to NGN4.59 billion, which was mainly supported by higher interest on bank deposits which stood at NGN3.89 billion in first quarter 2022 to NGN302.00 million in first quarter 2021. https://www.mtnonline.com Overall, pre-tax profit grew 39.4% year on year to NGN143.59 billion in first quarter 2022. However, a higher effective tax of 32.6% in first quarter 2022 compared to 28.4% in first quarter 2021 led to slower growth in profit after tax to NGN96.82 billion by 31.3% year on year. Comment: analysts at Cordros Research are of the opinion that beyond the solid topline growth delivered by MTNN, we are impressed with the growth in subscriber base during the quarter, which extended the rebound in fourth quarter 2021. “We also like the improvement in EBITDA margin despite the impact of currency devaluation on BTS lease cost amid elevated inflationary pressures. We would engage with management today to gain insights on the effect of NCC’s directive regarding NIN-SIM linkage and the eventual date of commencement of PSB operations, having obtained final approval from the Central bank.”